Host Michael McKean sorts out the problematic pedigrees of some of our favorite foods. Included: if German chocolate cake is iced with a grammatical error; if the real father of the French dip will please stand up; and if English muffins were spawned from some star-spangled batter.
Host Michael McKean learns how the milkshake got mixed up with home appliances, the Cobb salad became a Hollywood icon, and why Salisbury steak may be the one-way ticket to a better body.

Featured are a few sacred foods for special events. Host Michael McKean finds out why some people are handing out cake instead of candy on Halloween. Then, McKean discovers that Valentine's Day candy hearts were once used as medicine. Later, he figures out whether corned beef can really bring Irish luck on St. Patrick's Day.

Michael McKean studies the shapes of some favorite foods. He discovers that a pasta's figure is hiding a culinary code; that the pattern on a pineapple may unlock the mysteries of the universe; and that a chocolate's shape can transform its taste.

Host Roger Mooking cooks up two whole hogs in two different ways. Included: He visits MOPHO restaurant in New Orleans, where chef Michael Gulotta's Southeast Asian spit-roasted pig is a twist on a classic Southern tradition. Also: Mississippi chef Miles McMath hinges two steel troughs together to make a convenient and quick-cooking oven; and fries hand pies for dessert over an open flame.

In the Season 5 premiere, Roger Mooking meets a chef who uses a unique coal-fueled contraption called the Cross Table to roast butterflied pork marinated in bold achiote paste; and later, he simmers a seafood paella in a massive pan. Also: A trip to the OvenBird in Birmingham features a meat-lover's feast of lamb, rabbit and beef, along with seasonal veggies.

Savory and sweet flavors are found in Florida, where Roger meets a young pitmaster who pulls pork with a power tool and digs in to a sandwich called the Hamaburger. Later, a farmer preserving the tradition of making cane syrup is visited in Dade City.

Chef Roger Mooking visits Faith's Farm in Bonfield, Ill., where he's invited to take part in a feast cooked on three different fiery contraptions. Included: A whole lamb, boar steaks and pig skins are on the menu for this Latin and Mexican-inspired meal.

Roger attends the 100-year anniversary of the St. Mary Magdalene Church Picnic in Owensboro, Ky., where he helps hundreds of volunteers load and light three massive barbecue pits. Then, they get to business preparing several thousand pounds of meat, including mutton, pork butts and chickens.
